        "concepts_to_understand": "Focus groups are a qualitative data-gathering technique that brings together pre-qualified stakeholders to discuss a topic under the guidance of a facilitator. Unlike a survey, they allow for dynamic interaction and the collection of rich, detailed feedback. Unlike a public meeting, they are structured and controlled, ensuring that the discussion stays on track and that all participants have a chance to contribute. They are particularly useful for gathering feedback on a specific product, concept, or plan.",
        "additional_notes": "This question tests the candidate's ability to select the right tool for a specific type of qualitative data gathering. The scenario's key elements are a 'representative group,' the need for 'qualitative feedback' on 'specific concepts,' and the implied need for a controlled environment. A focus group perfectly fits this description. The other options are incorrect because they either lack the qualitative depth (survey) or the structured, controlled environment (town hall, interviews with a single person). The distinction between a focus group and a general public meeting is a key point tested here.",
