        "option_b_result": "CORRECT - Reserve Analysis is the most appropriate technique. The project manager needs to set aside money for 'identified risks.' This is the textbook definition of a contingency reserve. Reserve analysis is the process of establishing both contingency reserves (for known risks) and management reserves (for unknown risks) to account for project uncertainty. It is the specific tool for this purpose.",
        "option_c_result": "INCORRECT - A management reserve is a fund set aside for 'unknown-unknowns' and is controlled by senior management, not the project manager. The question specifies a need for a fund to cover 'identified risks,' which is a contingency reserve. This option misapplies the definition of management reserve.",
        "option_d_result": "INCORRECT - Earned Value Analysis is a performance measurement tool that compares actual performance to the project baseline. It is used during execution to monitor performance, not during planning to establish reserves.",
        "process_group": "Planning",
        "knowledge_area": "Risk",
