        "option_b_result": "INCORRECT - Resource leveling is used to resolve over-allocation, but it may extend the project's duration. The scenario explicitly states that the goal is to avoid an extension, making this option less appropriate than resource smoothing. The key distinction is the impact on the project's end date.",
        "option_c_result": "INCORRECT - While hiring a new resource is a possible solution, it is not a 'technique' or 'tool' in the same way that leveling or smoothing is. It's a resource acquisition strategy, which may be costly and time-consuming. It is not the most effective way in the context of schedule management techniques.",
        "option_d_result": "INCORRECT - This is a plausible action, but it may not be possible if the other team members lack the skills or capacity to perform the tasks. It is also not a standard project management 'technique' or 'tool.'",
        "process_group": "Planning",
        "knowledge_area": "Resources",
        "tool": "Resource Leveling",
        "suggested_read": "['PMBOK® Guide, 6th Edition, Section 6.6.2.1', 'PMI.org, Project Management Terminology']",
        "concepts_to_understand": "Resource smoothing is a variation of resource leveling that aims to keep resource usage at a consistent level. Unlike leveling, which may extend the project's duration, smoothing works within the existing total float of non-critical activities. It is used when the project's deadline is a hard constraint and the goal is to optimize resource usage without impacting the schedule's end date.",
        "additional_notes": "This question is difficult because it requires a precise understanding of the difference between resource leveling and resource smoothing. Both are resource optimization techniques, but they have different goals and outcomes. The key phrase 'without extending the project's final deadline' is the critical differentiator. Resource leveling might extend the project, but smoothing will not. The two close options are A and B, which tests a candidate's ability to distinguish between these two similar-sounding but different techniques. The other options are plausible actions but are not specific 'techniques' as defined by the PMBOK® Guide.",
