        "option_b_result": "INCORRECT - Arbitrarily lowering the risk priority is a dangerous approach. The low data quality does not mean the risk itself is less of a threat. It just means the assessment of the threat is unreliable. The risk may still be a high-priority risk.",
        "option_c_result": "CORRECT - The finding of a low-quality assessment means the project manager cannot rely on the results. The most appropriate and logical action is to improve the quality of the data. This involves gathering more objective information and consulting with a broader range of experts to get a more reliable assessment. This is a key step in ensuring the integrity of the risk management process.",
        "option_d_result": "INCORRECT - Using low-quality data to make important decisions about risk response is a poor practice. This could lead to an inappropriate response (e.g., spending too much on a low-priority risk or not enough on a high-priority risk) and is contrary to the purpose of the assessment.",
        "process_group": "Planning",
        "knowledge_area": "Risk",
        "tool": "Risk Data Quality Assessment",
        "suggested_read": "['PMBOK Guide, 6th Edition, Section 11.3.2.1', 'PMI Standards+™ - The Standard for Project Management']",
        "concepts_to_understand": "A key output of Risk Data Quality Assessment is an action plan to improve data quality when needed. This is a critical step before moving on to quantitative risk analysis or detailed response planning. If the input data is flawed, the output of any subsequent analysis will also be flawed. The project manager's role is to ensure the process is sound from the beginning.",
        "additional_notes": "This question is a good test of the candidate's understanding of the sequence and purpose of risk management processes. It's a 'what to do next' question based on a specific finding. The correct answer (collecting more data) directly addresses the problem identified in the assessment. The distractors are tempting because they are all legitimate risk management activities, but they are either the wrong tool for the situation (Monte Carlo) or represent poor decision-making (lowering priority, proceeding with bad data). The question's difficulty lies in the nuance of process flow and the proper application of the tools.",
