        "option_b_result": "CORRECT - Product analysis is the specific and most appropriate technique for taking a high-level product description and systematically refining it into a detailed set of requirements. This technique is used to clarify ambiguities and ensure the scope is well-defined. The examples of value engineering and product decomposition are correct sub-techniques.",
        "option_c_result": "INCORRECT - Stakeholder analysis is a separate process that identifies stakeholders and their needs. While it provides input, it is not the technique used to formally and systematically translate a product vision into a detailed scope.",
        "option_d_result": "INCORRECT - The RTM is a document used to link and track requirements. It is an output of the 'Collect Requirements' process and is used for management and control, not for the initial act of defining and detailing the scope.",
        "process_group": "Planning",
        "knowledge_area": "Scope",
