        "concepts_to_understand": "Roadmaps are versatile tools for communication that can be tailored to various audiences. For external stakeholders like vendors, a roadmap provides the necessary context—when key deliverables are due—without revealing the tactical, internal details that are irrelevant to them. This ensures clear and concise communication.",
        "additional_notes": "This question tests the candidate's understanding of the appropriate level of detail for communicating with external parties. The scenario highlights the need for a 'high-level, time-based format' that excludes 'internal tasks or resource assignments.' This is a perfect description of a project roadmap. A detailed schedule would violate the 'without seeing' clause, as it includes the exact type of information the project manager should not be sharing. The RBS and product backlog don't provide the timeline context required by the vendors. This question is considered difficult because it requires the candidate to not only know what a roadmap is but also to understand its role in external stakeholder communication and why other, seemingly related, documents are not appropriate due to their level of detail or purpose.",
